e", "prob": 0.961432933807373, "span": {"begin": 1518, "end": 1531}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-6", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918368458747864, "span": {"begin": 1533, "end": 1537}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tumor necrosis factor-alpha", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.993693470954895, "span": {"begin": 1543, "end": 1570}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7124"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TNF-&", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9874708652496338, "span": {"begin": 1572, "end": 1577}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3630"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "insulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9943842887878418, "span": {"begin": 1685, "end": 1692}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6720"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "SREBP-1c", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9917899966239929, "span": {"begin": 1730, "end": 1738}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9959248304367065, "span": {"begin": 1763, "end": 1766}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oxygen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9995267391204834, "span": {"begin": 1815, "end": 1821}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003681"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "oxidative stress", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9923793077468872, "span": {"begin": 1848, "end": 1864}}, {"id": ["CL:0000182"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hepatocyte", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7821873426437378, "span": {"begin": 1890, "end": 1900}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005234"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "steatosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999860525131226, "span": {"begin": 1956, "end": 1965}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:196"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AhR", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9948887228965759, "span": {"begin": 2008, "end": 2011}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:26291"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "fibroblast growth factor 21", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.998105525970459, "span": {"begin": 2035, "end": 2062}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:26291"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FGF21", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9926099181175232, "span": {"begin": 2064, "end": 2069}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3630"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "insulin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9905587434768677, "span": {"begin": 2116, "end": 2123}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005234"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "steatosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.999992847442627, "span": {"begin": 2173, "end": 2182}}], "text": "The aryl hydrocarbon receptor (AhR) is a ligand-activated transcription factor that mediates cellular responses to environmental toxins, dietary components, and endogenous metabolites. Upon ligand binding, AhR translocates to the nucleus, dimerizes with the aryl hydrocarbon receptor nuclear translocator (ARNT), and binds to xenobiotic response elements (XREs) in the promoter regions of target genes. While its primary function involves detoxification through the regulation of cytochrome P450 enzymes (e.g., CYP1A1, CYP1B1), chronic or excessive AhR activation is implicated in metabolic disorders, including liver steatosis (PMID:&nbsp;34830313, PMID:&nbsp;37284280).&nbsp;   AhR activation modulates lipid homeostasis through the upregulation of key lipogenic pathways. It regulates the expression of sterol regulatory element-binding protein 1c (SREBP-1c), a master regulator of fatty acid and triglyceride synthesis (PMID:&nbsp;29694888). Increased SREBP-1c expression enhances the transcription of lipogenic enzymes, such as acetyl-CoA carboxylase (ACC) and fatty acid synthase (FASN), leading to de novo lipogenesis (PMID:&nbsp;21029304). Concurrently, AhR increases the expression of CD36, a key transporter of fatty acids, which contributes to the import of these molecules in the cytoplasm and subsequently to de novo lipogenesis (PMID:&nbsp;20303349).&nbsp;   AhR activation also drives liver steatosis by inducing inflammatory responses. It promotes the production of pro-inflammatory cytokines, such as interleukin-6 (IL-6) and tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-&alpha;) (PMID:&nbsp;27713108). This inflammatory milieu exacerbates hepatic lipid accumulation by impairing insulin signaling, which further upregulates SREBP-1c activity. Additionally, AhR activation increases the production of reactive oxygen species (ROS), leading to oxidative stress, lipid peroxidation, and hepatocyte injury, all of which contribute to the pathogenesis of steatosis (PMID:&nbsp;34830313).&nbsp; Furthermore, AhR-mediated repression of fibroblast growth factor 21 (FGF21), a hormone critical for lipid metabolism and insulin sensitivity, has been implicated in exacerbating steatosis (PMID:&nbsp;27226639).&nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:06:31 +0000 2026"}